                        <h2 class="text-primary border-bottom border-primary border-3 pb-2 mb-4">The Basics</h2>

                        <h4 class="mt-4 mb-3">HTML: The Structure</h4>
                        <p>HTML (HyperText Markup Language) provides the structure of your webpage. Think of it as the skeleton of your website - it defines what content appears and how it's organized.</p>

                        <div class="bg-primary text-white rounded p-5 my-4 text-center">
                            <h5>Visual Diagram Placeholder</h5>
                        </div>

                        <h4 class="mt-4 mb-3">CSS: The Style</h4>
                        <p>CSS (Cascading Style Sheets) is responsible for the visual presentation. It controls colors, layouts, fonts, and animations - essentially everything that makes your website look good.</p>

                        <div class="alert alert-warning border-start border-4 border-warning" role="alert">
                            <strong>Key Point:</strong> Separating structure (HTML) from presentation (CSS) makes your code more maintainable and easier to update.
                        </div>

                        <h4 class="mt-4 mb-3">JavaScript: The Behavior</h4>
                        <p>JavaScript adds interactivity to your pages. From simple button clicks to complex animations and data processing, JavaScript brings your website to life.</p>
                    </section>

                    <section id="practice" class="mb-5">
                        <h2 class="text-primary border-bottom border-primary border-3 pb-2 mb-4">Practical Example</h2>
                        <p>Let's put these concepts together with a simple example. Below is a basic structure of an HTML document:</p>

                        <div class="bg-light border rounded p-3 my-4">
                            <pre class="mb-0"><code>&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;
                                &lt;html&gt;
                                  &lt;head&gt;
                                    &lt;title&gt;My First Page&lt;/title&gt;
                                  &lt;/head&gt;
                                  &lt;body&gt;
                                    &lt;h1&gt;Hello, World!&lt;/h1&gt;
                                    &lt;p&gt;This is my first webpage.&lt;/p&gt;
                                  &lt;/body&gt;
                                &lt;/html&gt;</code></pre>
                        </div>

                        <p>This simple example demonstrates the basic structure every HTML page should have. The head contains metadata, while the body contains the visible content.</p>
